Constructor initialization of member variables

There is 3 ways to initialize member variables when constructor is called.

1)	Using Member Initializer List: 
	This is the syntax used to initialize member variables of a class before the body of the constructor executes. 

	PhoneBook::PhoneBook( void ) : count(0) 
	{
		//empty
	} 	

	'count' is a member variable of PhoneBook class.
	'count' can be private or public.

2)  Assignment within the constructor body. 
	(Directly)

	PhoneBook::PhoneBook( void ) 
	{
		this->count = 0;
	} 	

Situations where you might prefer assignment in the constructor body:

If the initialization involves complex logic, conditional statements, or error handling, 
it can be clearer and more manageable to use assignment within the constructor body.

Example:

class Example 
{
    int _count;
public:
    Example(int value) 
   {
        if (value < 0) 
            _count = 0;  // Default to 0 if negative
        else 
            _count = value;
    }
};

3) 	Assignment within the constructor body. 
	(using setter function)

	ex: 
	instead of :	this->_count = value;
	you can call setter function: 
					this->setter(value);
	Why? because you may want to have additional logic (e.g., validation) in the setter function.
	It's better to use setter fucntion to maintain consistency.


